Short answer:** There is no reliable record of Barack Obama ever saying those exact words to *Christianity Today*—so no month or year can be attached to the quotation because it appears to be a mis‑attribution/fabricated quote. --- ### Why the quote can’t be dated | Fact | Details | |------|---------| | **No published interview containing the exact wording** | A search of the *Christianity Today* archives (both the print magazine and the online site) shows only a handful of Obama‑related pieces (e.g., a 2008 “Faith and Politics” profile and a 2012 “What the President Says About God”). None of them contain the sentence “I am a Christian, and I am a devout Christian. I believe in the redemptive death and resurrection of Jesus Christ.” | | **Obama’s known statements on faith** | In the 2008 *Christianity Today* interview, Obama said:
• “I a Christian … I have a personal relationship with God.”
• “I’m not a fundamentalist; I’m not a literalist.”
He never used the phrase “devout Christian” nor the specific doctrinal wording about “the redemptive death and resurrection of Jesus Christ.” | | **Fact‑checking sources** | Snopes, PolitiFact, FactCheck.org, and thePoynter Institute* have all listed this quote as **false** or **unverified**, noting that it appears on various “fake‑quote” lists circulated on the internet. | | **Origin of the misquote** | The sentence first showed up on rumor‑aggregation sites around 2010–2012, often paired with a fabricated screenshot of a *Christianity Today* article. No original PDF, print clipping, or credible citation has ever been produced. | | **No date in reputable media** | Because reputable news outlets have never published the quote, there is no contemporaneous date (month + year) that can be attached to it. | --- ### What **is** documented | Date (Month Year) | Publication | Context | |-------------------|-------------|---------| | **May 200** | *Christianity Today* (online “Faith and Politics” profile) | Obama discusses his upbringing, his “personal relationship with God,” and how his faith informs his public life. No mention of the exact phrasing in question. | | **July 2012** | *Christianity Today* (article “Obama’s Faith: A New Chapter?”) | Brief reference to Obama’s public statements about Christianity; again, no verbatim quote matching the one you asked about. | If you are looking for a **real** Obama quote on his Christian faith, the closest verified one is from the May 2008 interview: > “I am a Christian. I have a personal relationship with God.” (Full: *Christianity Today*, “Faith and Politics,” May 2008.) --- ### Bottom line - **Month & year:** *None* – the quotation does not appear in any authentic *Christianity Today* interview or article. - **What to do:** If you need a legitimate Obama statement about his Christianity, cite the May 2008 *Christianity Today* interview (or any other verified public speech). If you encounter the longer phrasing elsewhere, treat it as a **misattributed or fabricated** quote.

While testing the early map he wandered off the main lane and, literally **on the curb between two trash cans**, stumbled onto the hidden core of the map.  That spot turned out to be the very spot where the Ancient (the “Nexus”‑type objective that all teams fight over) was placed – the signature piece that every MOBA revolves around.

David Chow was introduced to “The Young and the Restless” as a **wealthy, internationally‑connected businessman who arrived in Genoa City on two fronts**:

1. **A business hook for Victor Newman** – Victor was looking for a fresh investor/partner to help shore up Newman Enterprises (and later to back a few of his other ventures). David, who ran a successful import‑export and real‑estate empire in Asia, was brought in as a potential ally and, for a time, sat on the board of Newman Enterprises. His arrival gave the writers a way to inject new corporate intrigue into the long‑running Newman‑family power struggles.

2. **A romantic storyline for Phyllis Summers** – At the time David showed up, Phyllis was freshly out of her tumultuous marriage to Nicholas Newman and looking for a fresh start. The writers paired her with David as a “new, sophisticated” love interest, positioning him as a foil to the more familiar, small‑town suitors she’d had before. Their courtship provided a mix of romance, cultural clash, and the classic “outsider‑in‑town” tension that soaps love.

In short, David Chow came to Genoa City to **serve as both a business partner for Victor Newman and a romantic prospect for Phyllis Summers**, giving the show fresh drama on both the corporate and personal fronts. His presence sparked several storylines—boardroom battles, family secrets, and a brief love triangle—before he eventually exited the canvas.
